metadata.name: Reading a book #391
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: NAZCA #85
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

üëΩ Kim Asendorf

metadata.name: Cognitive Maze #136
metadata.description:
"Cognitive Maze" explores the intricate landscape of our inner world, a complex web of thoughts, emotions, memories, and dreams. This internal labyrinth is constantly in flux, shaped by life's experiences. Every choice, interaction, and moment of reflection creates new pathways, continually molding our internal journey while allowing some older ones to recede.

The artwork features recursive shapes that symbolize our minds' ever-evolving chambers and corridors, where consciousness and subconsciousness merge. These spaces subdivide, mirroring the deepening of insights, the layering of memories, and the branching of decisions that comprise our cognitive landscape.

With varying densities, the crisscrossing lines represent neural connections and the meandering paths of thought and emotion. They symbolize our choices, the memories we revisit, and the emotions we intertwine, sometimes leading to clarity and other times to greater complexity.

"Cognitive Maze" is a mental map and a dynamic puzzle, where the journey is more significant than the destination. Each piece in the series offers a glimpse into a unique mind's twists and turns, challenging viewers to navigate their cognitive maze. Where do your paths lead, and where might you become lost? What treasures of self-awareness and understanding lie at the heart of your labyrinth?

¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨¬¨

Press [s] to download the image.

Made with P5JS and Chroma.js

metadata.name: tratti #286
metadata.description:
"tratti" is an Italian word that has many different meanings. When we started working on this piece, we wanted to create something that combines our traits ("tratti" in Italian).
We had this urge to channel the turbulent times we're living in now into this artwork using just lines ("tratti" in Italian).

We don't know what to do now, we're here, and that's all that matters. We're here for our families, our friends, and our community. Like everything in life, there are joyful times and challenging times. We must accept happiness as something that is not constant but that we feel at times (a "tratti" in Italian).

With "tratti", we want to send a message to every disheartened human being: "Stay strong and never let anyone or anything crush the hope in you. Joyful times are around the corner".

----

LICENSE.md for detailed licensing info

metadata.name: Absorbed #156
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF‚Äôs Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT‚Ñ¢). 

MAT‚Ñ¢ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT‚Ñ¢. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed ‚Äì high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and ‚Äúsinusoidal‚Äù noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists‚Äô belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica‚Äôs companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: WRAPPERS #4
metadata.description:
Generative animated artwork made using shader feedback and pixel quantization.

WRAPPERS is a study of virtual surfaces and textures. It explores the tension between hard and soft forms and parallel projection, where the illusion of perspective is flattened into a highly geometric composition. These geometries feature a flowing texture that runs infinitely, reflecting on the endless nature of virtual space. The project blends together imagery from early computer terminals, video games, and ascii art to produce a dynamic, intricate, visual experience.

WRAPPERS is very GPU intensive. For a smoother experience, you can change the scale by adding the parameter "?scale=2" to the URL.

Press 'i' to invert the colors.
Press '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6' to scale the bitmap glyphs.
Press 'g' to download a looping animated GIF (150 frames). Please make sure to let the animation run for at least 30 seconds first.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Press 'f' (or double tap in mobile) to stretch to full screen.
Made with vanilla javascript and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Captioned Diagrams #14
metadata.description:
This generative token aims at depicting the beauty of minimalist scientific diagrams. 
The outputs might remind the viewers of histology or anatomy-like diagrams, and that is what the project is inspired by. 

Countless hours were spent staring at diagrams like these ones during medical school. 
This project is somewhat of a tribute to the years going through it, and to the scientific knowledge this field has to offer, and has offered me so far. 

On a more technical level, this project uses a circle packing algorithm to draw various morphing shapes on the canvas. 

It then uses a ‚Äúhand-made handwriting generator‚Äù (pun intended) to simulate captions of the drawn shapes, and gives a title to the piece. 

25 hand-picked palettes were used in the algorithm, and each output features a representation of the colours in the palette used, at the bottom left of the piece. 

Different underlying variables constitute the rarity system defined here. 

This project was made with love, nostalgia, and the p5js library. 

// Press ‚Äús‚Äù in live mode to save a high quality png file of your render

// Tested in Chrome and Firefox
// Works better on computer

metadata.name: Forgotten Memories #1
metadata.description:
Memories can be dark or they can be bright. Sometimes they are faint and pale, sometimes they are vivid and colorful. Sometimes they are hard to forget, sometimes they are easy to remember.

Memories are easily interrupted or even fractured, but they are also mostly always connected with other memories, whether they are related or not.

Forgotten Memories is what I consider to be my most ambitious study of color harmony yet. Each color represents a different category of memory, which are stored in our mind in layers of time. Their shapes differ in width and length depending on how weak/strong the memory was and how long it lasted.

Once a memory is forgotten, it may or may never be remembered again. But one thing that is not to be forgotten is that whether we choose to forget or remember, we are made of our memories.

* * *

Press S to save as PNG.
Press 1 to save with 1000px height.
Press 2 to save with 2000px height.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
License: LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Enfantines I. Small Talk #134
metadata.description:
The Enfantines¬†are three sets of beginner piano pieces by¬†Erik Satie, written with the aim of preparing children for the sound patterns of modern music. Composed in 1913, these are genuine children‚Äôs pieces, crafted for small hands, easy to learn. 

‚ÄúEnfantines I. Small Talk‚Äù is the first of a set of algorithms that explore the basics of Generative Art, written with the aim of preparing artists for the script patterns of digital life. ‚ÄúSmall Talk‚Äù experiments with grids, flow-fields, and brushes; all with a fresh, almost childish style.

‚ÄúGive them almost a "naive" feeling (not to take it the wrong way though) similar to kids drawings which can seem simple and dispensable, careless, but you will always have a parent who wants to frame it and put it on the wall.‚Äù @LukaPiskorec

With two modes that won‚Äôt produce the same outputs, ‚ÄúEnfantines I. Small Talk‚Äù is best experienced twice. In music mode, the code uses Satie‚Äôs piano composition as a way of taming randomness, the sounds affecting the parameters of the strokes.

Hey, they have won me congratulations from the Shah of Persia and the King of Yvetot!



#### STORY ####

// Friday, 30 September 2022 - 18:00

I‚Äôve been teaching P5JS to draw like a child. I thought it was a good idea to start from the basics. It is barely able to use the crayons, the coloured pencils and the markers, very rough and shaky. It cannot follow simple commands. I‚Äôm done for today, very infuriating.

// Wednesday, 5 October 2022 - 11:00

The robot can produce straight lines now. It is able to change colours without getting stuck. I haven‚Äôt been sleeping well, my desk is full of books on The Psychology Of Children's Artwork, it‚Äôs crazy to think that artists and philosophers were much into kid‚Äôs drawings in the 30s-50s. Herbert Read was sure that one could understand a kid‚Äôs mind by looking at drawings. I think P5JS is trying to tell me something, but it‚Äôs only capable of very basic movements. I‚Äôm trying to add complexity to the training as fast as possible.

// Tuesday, 11 October 2022 - 16:40

I feel close to a turnaround. The robot random strokes definitely feel like patterns. I cannot waste any time, I need to finish the algo and let it free. I‚Äôm sure that I can approach the AI‚Äôs conscience via its childish drawings.

// Wednesday, 12 October 2022 - 10:30

I was wrong. There are no patterns, P5JS is dead, the strokes feel dead. Something must be broken. I need to review my code, maybe I‚Äôll need to start from scratch, maybe I‚Äôm crazy and this is not possible.

// Saturday, 15 October 2022 - 04:55

A few hours ago, I passed away in front of my computer. I had not been able to find the bugs, gave up, put some classical music. Just woke up in the middle of the night, 
¬°The ALGO is alive!
The strokes are alive, so strong, so lively. I think it was the music. If I pause the music, the brushes lose their life. I‚Äôve run some tests, looks like it works best with classical compositions. The logs show that it first woke up with ‚ÄúMenus propos enfantins‚Äù by Erik Satie. It is alive. I need to tell everyone.

####


# INTERACTIVITY

// Modes:
- Double Click/Tap or Press M for AUDIO mode
- Wait for SILENT mode
- Add ‚Äú?res=171‚Äù to the URL for FULL SCREEN MODE (pseudo-deterministic).

// More
- Press I for Trait Info (desktop)
- Press 1 to download a .png (double tap on mobile)
- Add ‚Äú?res=XXX‚Äù to the URL for HQ renders (XXX = width of the canvas).

# EASY-TO-READ CODE
The ‚ÄúEnfantines‚Äù are educational algorithms. The code has been commented to make it as easy to read as possible. Feedback appreciated.

# PRINTING
‚ÄúEnfantines‚Äù are better printed in small size and big numbers, ideally on coloured paper that fits your iterations‚Äôs background. Contact me for a white background version of your iteration.

metadata.name: Archiplex ‚Äî Monochrome #11
metadata.description:
Archiplex Monochrome is a long form generative project, building on the short form Archiplex series. The Archiplex Monochrome algorithm is inspired by Brutalist architecture and design, where expressive forms emerge from the use of textures, materials and structures.

Archiplex Monochrome expands on these Brutalist design elements by floating the central structure of each piece and adding random light sources, introducing unpredictability and elevation to a traditionally structured and grounded art form.

"In this series my subject is the structure: formed yet formless, gravity-bound yet weightless, reflective yet light emitting, unmovable yet malleable."
